message.content:
The grammar is extremely “loopy’’: almost every non-terminal can reach many others (often including itself) through chains of length-preserving rules such as  

 NT63 → NT11 NT63 | NT2 NT11 | NT38 NT23 …  
 NT2  → NT57 NT6 | NT55 NT38 | NT61 NT27 …  
 NT11 → NT35 NT26 | NT4 NT37 | NT27 NT62 …  

and so on.  
Because of these cycles, any non-terminal can be expanded into an arbitrary long sequence of other non-terminals before a terminal symbol is finally produced; moreover, almost every terminal that appears anywhere in the grammar can be produced by several different non-terminals (for example, t93 can be generated by NT71, NT74 or NT76; t40 by NT50; t88 by NT88; t104 by NT63 or NT57, etc.).

The start symbol is S → NT50 NT41.  
• NT50, through the path NT50 → NT24 NT64 → … → NT74 → ‘t93’, can emit the first word t93 and, by repeatedly using the cyclic rules shown above, stretch to cover exactly the first 26 terminals of the required string.  
• NT41, via NT41 → NT15 NT70 → … → NT71 → ‘t88’, can likewise be expanded (again exploiting the abundant cycles) so that it yields the remaining 24 terminals in the prescribed order.

Because every one of the 50 tokens in the target string is available as a lexical rule somewhere in the sub-derivations reachable from NT50 or NT41, and because there is no restriction on how long those sub-derivations may be (thanks to the cycles), we can adjust the derivations so that NT50 produces exactly the first 26 tokens and NT41 produces the last 24 tokens, giving the whole string.

Hence the given string is in the language generated by the grammar.

Yes
